  "text": "The FWER is a very strict criterion. When thousands and even millions of hypotheses are tested simultaneously, the FWER procedures often become excessively conservative and fail to identify most useful signals. This often results in the waste of expensive studies and possible financial losses. In large-scale settings, a more powerful and practical error rate concept is the false discovery rate (FDR, [CITATION_1] . Under the FDR paradigm, one is willing to tolerate some Type I errors, provided that the number is small relative to the total number of rejections. Define the false discovery proportion",
  "correct_citation": {
